message-router.ts:154-553 — every browser command handler follows this pattern: (params, id) => { if (id !== undefined) { handleFoo(params, id).catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] browser.foo handler failed:', err)); } }. Some handlers are sync (getNetworkRequests, disableNetworkCapture, getConsoleLogs, clearConsoleLogs) and don't have .catch(). Extract two helpers:

const wrapAsync = (method: string, fn: (params: Record<string, unknown>, id: string | number) => Promise<void>): MessageHandler => (params, id) => { if (id !== undefined) fn(params, id).catch((err: unknown) => console.warn(`[opentabs] ${method} handler failed:`, err)); };

const wrapSync = (fn: (params: Record<string, unknown>, id: string | number) => void): MessageHandler => (params, id) => { if (id !== undefined) fn(params, id); };

Then each entry becomes: ['browser.listTabs', wrapAsync('browser.listTabs', handleBrowserListTabs)]. Some handlers take only id (no params) — the wrapper still passes params, the handler ignores them. This is fine because the type is already (params, id) => void. Note: some handlers like sync.full and plugin.update don't check id !== undefined (they are notifications). Keep those as-is (or create a wrapNotification helper). The test in known-methods.test.ts checks methodHandlerNames which is derived from methodHandlers.keys() — this won't be affected.
